create a  docker container with ubuntu image using docker run cmd  and get inside the container install tomcat on it and host a simple website 

Step 1: Run Ubuntu Container

docker run -it --name ubuntu-tomcat -p 8080:8080 ubuntu:20.04 /bin/bash

This command:

Starts an interactive Ubuntu container
Names it ubuntu-tomcat
Maps port 8080 of the container to your host
Opens a bash shell inside the container


Step 2: Inside the Container â€“ Install Java and Tomcat

Once inside the container:

# Update package list
apt-get update

# Install Java (required for Tomcat)
apt-get install -y openjdk-11-jdk wget

# Set JAVA_HOME (optional but good practice)
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-11-openjdk-amd64
export PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH

# Download and extract Tomcat
wget https://downloads.apache.org/tomcat/tomcat-9/v9.0.83/bin/apache-tomcat-9.0.83.tar.gz
tar -xvzf apache-tomcat-9.0.83.tar.gz
mv apache-tomcat-9.0.83 /opt/tomcat

Step 3: Add a Simple Website
Create a basic HTML file:

mkdir /opt/tomcat/webapps/ROOT
echo "<html><body><h1>Hello from Tomcat on Ubuntu Docker!</h1></body></html>" > /opt/tomcat/webapps/ROOT/index.html


Step 4: Start Tomcat

##############################################

To convert your running Ubuntu container (with Tomcat and your website installed) into a Docker image using the docker commit command, follow these steps:

Step 1: Exit the Container (if you're still inside)
Press Ctrl + P then Ctrl + Q to detach from the container without stopping it.

Step 2: Commit the Container to an Image

docker commit ubuntu-tomcat pradeep/ubuntu-tomcat:v1

This command:

Takes the container named ubuntu-tomcat
Creates a new image named pradeep/ubuntu-tomcat with tag v1


Step 3: Run the New Image

docker run -d -p 8080:8080 pradeep/ubuntu-tomcat:v1

This will start a new container from your custom image and expose Tomcat on port 8080.

